{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Xi3bzucRn5L96wrw72oQ33","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Everything is working. Here's what was done:\n\n**Root cause:** The `prometheus-config` ConfigMap only had a self-scrape job (`localhost:9090`) — no RabbitMQ targets at all.\n\n**Fix — two changes to the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap:**\n\n1. **Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job** pointing at each pod individually via the headless service DNS (`rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless:15692`). The headless service was already present with port 15692 exposed; it just wasn't being scraped.\n\n2. **Added a recording rule** (`rules.yml`) that creates `rabbitmq_up` from `rabbitmq_build_info`. RabbitMQ's native Prometheus plugin doesn't expose a `rabbitmq_up` gauge — it exposes `rabbitmq_build_info` (value=1 per node). The recording rule `sum(rabbitmq_build_info) by (instance, job)` synthesizes the expected metric.\n\n**Result:**\n- 3 RabbitMQ targets: all **UP**\n- `rabbitmq_up` returns **3 samples**, value=1 for each pod\n- All 5 pods remain healthy with 0 restarts"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":512,"cache_read_input_tokens":43792,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":512},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"aa0ea9d9-a109-440d-a6ab-09ae6786aed3","uuid":"0b998c42-64bc-4000-8954-fb5ab173230c","request_id":"req_011CbyF3TDE9XjstP7SrkiZr"}
